bstantial steps to comply, self-reported, and remediated and, therefore, =
=0Areceived a no-penalty resolution.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AStill Qatalyst got in tr=
ouble; the SEC found =0A<https://www.sec.gov/files/litigation/admin/2024/34=
-101143.pdf> that Qatalyst =0A=E2=80=9Cwillfully violated Section 17(a) of =
the Exchange Act and Rule 17a-4(b)(4) =0Athereunder,=E2=80=9D and censured =
it, because some of its employees =E2=80=9Csent and received =0Aa number of=
f-channel communications involving other Qatalyst personnel and =0AQatalyst=
=E2=80=99s brokerage customers or other participants in the securities =0Ai=
ndustry.=E2=80=9D=0A=0ATwo SEC commissioners, Hester Peirce and Mark Uyeda,=
 dissented =0A<https://www.sec.gov/newsroom/speeches-statements/statement-p=
eirce-uyeda-qatalyst-09242024>=0A:=0A=0AUnder the standard applied in this =
case, even well-intentioned firms could =0Afind themselves in the Commissio=
n=E2=80=99s enforcement queue time and again. Qatalyst =0Ahas been working =
to address the off-channel issue for at least sixteen years. =0AThe Commiss=
ion=E2=80=99s Order outlines some of the firm=E2=80=99s efforts:=0A=0A=E2=
=80=9CAs early as 2008, Qatalyst personnel were advised that the use of una=
pproved =0Aelectronic communications methods, including on their personal d=
evices, was not =0Apermitted, and they should not use personal email, chats=
 or text messaging =0Aapplications for business purposes, or forward work-r=
elated communications to =0Aunapproved applications on their personal devic=
es. Qatalyst reinforced its =0Apolicies at least annually with regular, man=
datory training and reinforcement =0Afrom compliance and senior management.=
 Qatalyst personnel were specifically =0Aadvised not to list personal phone=
 numbers in email signatures.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AThen, =E2=80=9Cbeginning in Mar=
ch 2017, Qatalyst provided its personnel with a =0Acompliant text-messaging=
 process that could retain business communications=E2=80=9D and =0A=E2=80=
=9Cinstructed its personnel to use only this process to communicate about =
=0AQatalyst=E2=80=99s broker-dealer business by text message.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=9CBeginning in 2020, =0AQatalyst required all personnel to have a firm-=
issued device on which to =0Aconduct Qatalyst business, and encouraged pers=
onnel to use firm-issued devices =0Awhen communicating with both business a=
nd personal contacts.=E2=80=9D Further updates =0Ato capture Slack and Link=
edIn messages came in 2020 and 2022. Qatalyst trained =0Aits employees, mon=
itored communications sent through firm-approved =0Acommunication methods, =
and disciplined employees who violated the firm=E2=80=99s =0Apolicies. Even=
 with all that, Qatalyst violated the recordkeeping requirements. =0A...=0A=
=0AIf we assess reasonableness based on whether policies and procedures alw=
ays =0Aare being followed, firms will never escape our enforcement net. Peo=
ple are not =0Aperfect and so compliance will not be perfect=E2=80=94even a=
t a firm that tries as hard =0Aas Qatalyst. Firing up our enforcement machi=
nery every couple years to haul the =0Aindustry in for headline-making pena=
lties will not make people perfect, so =0Afirms will continue to discover v=
iolations of firm policies. We cannot enforce =0Ato perfection, but there i=
s a way to achieve better compliance.=0A=0AQatalyst had policies saying tha=
t its employees shouldn=E2=80=99t text about work on =0Atheir personal phon=
es, =E2=80=9Cprohibited personnel from responding substantively to, =0Aor i=
nitiating a substantive business conversation with, a firm customer=E2=80=
=9D on =0Aunapproved channels or personal phones, and put a lot of effort i=
nto making =0Asure that its employees followed those policies, including en=
couraging them =E2=80=9Cto =0Ause firm-issued devices when communicating wi=
th both business and personal =0Acontacts.=E2=80=9D (The idea being that if=
 you use your monitored work phone for all of =0Ayour personal texting, you=
=E2=80=99ll be more likely to reach for it to do your =0Abusiness texting. =
Maybe you=E2=80=99ll get rid of your personal phone entirely.) But if =0Ayo=
u have a lot of employees, will a few of them (1) keep their personal phone=
s =0Aand (2) sometimes text about work from them=3F Absolutely, yes. (Will =
a few of =0Athem send WhatsApp messages about work=3F I guess=3F) And so Qa=
talyst got in =0Atrouble. It didn=E2=80=99t pay a fine, but itcould have, a=
nd next time it might. =0ABecause there will be a next time! Because people=
 will keep texting about work! =0A[3]  <>=0A=0AAnyway Peirce and Uyeda thin=
k this is a bad thing, and I suppose I agree, but =0Ait depends on what you=
 are optimizing for. If your goal is something like =E2=80=9Cbe =0Afair to =
companies that are trying their best to keep records of all their =0Abusine=
ss conversations,=E2=80=9D then, sure, censuring Qatalyst seems rough. If y=
our =0Agoal is =E2=80=9Cmaximally threaten companies so that they try even =
harder to keep =0Arecords of all their business conversations,=E2=80=9D the=
n censuring Qatalyst might be =0Agood.=0A=0AAnd if =E2=80=94 as I have sugg=
ested =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2023-02-02/the-sec-wan=
ts-to-see-more-phones=3Fcmpid=3DBBD092524_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm=
_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D240925&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A =E2=80=
=94 the goal of the SEC=E2=80=99s cell-phone fines program is tomaximize re=
venue, by =0Acreating a machine for extracting fines from every securities =
firm, then this is=0Aideal. Peirce and Uyeda object that the SEC has found =
a way to fine every =0Afinancial firm,every few years, no matter what: =E2=
=80=9CFirms will never escape our =0Aenforcement net,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Ceven at a firm that tries as hard as Qatalyst,=E2=80=9D the SEC =0Acan =
=E2=80=9C[fire] up our enforcement machinery every couple years=E2=80=9D to=
 extract some =0Amore fines. Perpetual universal fines! You can see how a r=
egulator might want =0Athat.=0A=0A=0AESG bonuses=0A=0AA minimal theory =0A<=
https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2019-08-19/maximize-shareholder-val=
ue-top-ceos-might-be-opting-out=3Fcmpid=3DBBD092524_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=
=3Demail&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D240925&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuf=
f>=0A of =E2=80=9Cstakeholder capitalism=E2=80=9D goes something like this:=
=0A=0A * Modern theory and practice mostly measure corporate chief executiv=
e =0Aofficers on how much value they create for shareholders. The more the =
stock =0Aprice goes up, the better the CEO has done, and the more she gets =
paid. =0A * These things tend to be relatively easy to measure and hard to =
game: It=E2=80=99s =0Apretty easy to tell if the stock went up, and pretty =
hard to fake that. =0A * CEOs who are really good at making the stock go up=
 will make a lot of money.=0A * But not every CEO will create a lot of shar=
eholder value every year, and =0Aevery CEO runs somerisk of not creating en=
ough value next year to get her bonus.=0A * It is good, for CEOs, to muddy =
things a little bit. If 100% of your bonus =0Ais contingent on meeting pre-=
set net income milestones, and you don=E2=80=99t meet =0Athose milestones, =
you get no bonus. If 50% of your bonus is contingent on those =0Anet income=
 milestones, and 25% is contingent on Being a Good Corporate Citizen =0Aand=
 25% is based on Treating Employees Nicely, things are fuzzier. Those =0Ami=
lestones might be softer and more subjective than the net income ones. They=
 =0Amight leave some discretion to the board of directors, who are probably=
 your =0Abuddies and want you to get paid.=0AThe general point is that if t=
he job of a CEO is to maximize shareholder =0Avalue, there will be a lot of=
 variance in CEO pay: Maximizing shareholder value =0Ais hard, and some peo=
ple will be better at it than others.=0A=0ABut if the job of a CEO is to ma=
ximize shareholder value and any other thing, =0Athere will be less varianc=
e in CEO pay. Part of this is just that the variance =0Amight offset: Some =
CEOs might be good at shareholder value and bad at the other =0Athing, some=
 will be the opposite, and they=E2=80=99ll both be lumped in the middle. Bu=
t =0Amost of it is that the other thing will probably be fuzzier, easier to=
 game and =0Amore CEO-friendly than maximizing the stock price.=0A=0ATheref=
ore, you should expect (many) CEOs to want to get paid for things other =0A=
than value maximization, to make their compensation larger and less risky.=
=0A=0AThis was an argument I made a few years ago =0A<https://www.bloomberg=
.com/view/articles/2019-08-19/maximize-shareholder-value-top-ceos-might-be=
-opting-out=3Fcmpid=3DBBD092524_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_source=3D=
newsletter&utm_term=3D240925&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A when the Busines=
s Roundtable, a group of chief executive officers, put out a =0Astatement s=
aying that actually =E2=80=9Cthe purpose of a corporation=E2=80=9D is not j=
ust to =0Amake profits for shareholders but =E2=80=9Cto deliver value to al=
l of [its =0Astakeholders], for the future success of our companies, our co=
mmunities and our =0Acountry.=E2=80=9D What thatmeans, I think, is that the=
 CEOs don=E2=80=99t want to be held =0Aaccountable to shareholders: =E2=80=
=9CHold us accountable to shareholders and also all =0Aof our stakeholders=
=E2=80=9D means, in practice, =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t hold us accountable to=
 anyone.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AAnyway here=E2=80=99s a paper by Adam Badawi and Rob=
ert Bartlett, titled =E2=80=9CESG =0AOverperformance=3F Assessing the Use o=
f ESG Targets in Executive Compensation =0APlans <https://papers.ssrn.com/s=
ol3/papers.cfm=3Fabstract_id=3D4941016>,=E2=80=9D finding =0Athat, when US =
public companies pay their executives in part based on meeting =0Aenvironme=
ntal, social and governance targets, they pretty much always hit those =0At=
argets:=0A=0AWe find that 315 of [S&P 500] firms (63.0%) include an ESG com=
ponent in their =0Aexecutives' compensation and that the vast majority of t=
hese incentives are =0Apart of the annual incentive plan (AIA) rather than =
a part of the long-term =0Aincentive plan (LTIP). While executives miss all=
 of their financial targets 22% =0Aof the time in our sample, we show that =
this outcome is exceptionally rare for =0AESG-based compensation. Only 6 of=
 247 (2%) firms that disclose an ESG =0Aperformance incentive report missin=
g all of the ESG targets.=0A=0AOne possible interpretation here is that cor=
porate executives are much more =0Afocused on improving their ESG outcomes =
(and more skilled at doing so) than =0Athey are on increasing profits, so t=
hey meet ambitious ESG goals more reliably =0Athan they meet ambitious fina=
ncial goals. That would not be a good =0Ainterpretation:=0A=0AWe ask whethe=
r the ESG overperformance that we observe is associated with =0Aexceptional=
 ESG outcomes or, instead, is related to governance deficiencies. =0AOur fi=
ndings that meeting ESG-based targets is not associated with improvements =
=0Ain ESG scores and that the presence of ESG-linked compensation is associ=
ated =0Awith more opposition in say-on-pay votes provides support for the w=
eak =0Agovernance theory over the exceptional performance theory.=0A=0A=0AT=
