tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if shareholders are really unhappy with you, t=
here can be a proxy fight, which is a binding, non-symbolic director electi=
on: An activist shareholder can nominate its own director candidates to joi=
n the board, make changes=C2=A0and supervise you. This is expensive and dif=
ficult, but sometimes an activist will win some board seats. You can protec=
t yourself, though, with a =E2=80=9Cclassified board=E2=80=9D: Instead of h=
aving all of your directors elected each year, the directors have staggered=
 three-year terms, so only one-third of them are elected each year. Then, e=
ven if an activist wins a proxy fight, it will get only one-third of the bo=
ard seats, and can=E2=80=99t outvote you.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">O=
f course at that point the board meetings could get very awkward, since you=
r board is now two-thirds your buddies and one-third your critics. You can =
